SIMPLE: pore
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pore
<hw>Pore</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>porus</ets>, Gr. <?/ a passage, a pore. See <er>Fare</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of the minute orifices in an
animal or vegetable membrane, for transpiration, absorption,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A minute opening or passageway; an interstice
between the constituent particles or molecules of a body; <as>as, the
<ex>pores</ex> of stones</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pore</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pore
<hw>Pore</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Pored</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Poring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>poren</ets>, of
uncertain origin; cf. D. <ets>porren</ets> to poke, thrust, Gael.
<ets>purr</ets>.]</ety> <def>To look or gaze steadily in reading or
studying; to fix the attention; to be absorbed; -- often with
<xex>on</xex> or <xex>upon</xex>, and now usually with
<xex>over</xex>.</def>⟦ldquo⟧Painfully to <xex>pore</xex> upon a
book.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The eye grows weary with <qex>poring</qex> perpetually on the same
thing.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Poreblind</ent>⟦br⟧
